post_text:
Meet Stephanie Cummings, teacher at Fairview Elementary! Mrs. Cummings has shared a poem she wrote about remote learning and being a Senator! #SenatorsLearn #SenatorPride #SenatorsCare
"Zoom, Freckle, Adobe Spark and more,
I am ready to venture into the virtual world and soar!
Working on relationships, academics and routine,
Will be challenging but bring lots of smiles on our screen.
Teammates continue to be my family and support,
Fourth grade at Fairview will definitely not cut our students short!
“Shake if off” will continue to be my year’s motto,
Becoming a Senator five years ago was like winning the lotto!
Let us start this school year with cheers and applause,
Us teachers are about to be dropping some parents' jaws!"

post_text:
Meet Dr. Lane Carter, English teacher at Dover High School! She had this to say about remote learning: “This spring, the reality of remote teaching bloomed into Capital School District. Were we ready? Absolutely not. However, our terrific team at the district and school levels dug into the challenge. I've enjoyed every moment of the technological immersion (bitmoji, Classtag, Loom, Schoology, Edmentum). Yet, my best times are always spent talking with my individual students, and technology opens our ears to better one-on-one conferencing. Join us for another walk on the virtual wild-side!”
#SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare #SenatorPride

post_text: Mrs. Carissa Weekes initially did not start off wanting to be a teacher. However, volunteering in the classrooms of her siblings when they attended Fairview Elementary changed her mind. “I love being able to share my love of reading with students and develop relationships with the students and families at Towne Point. I also love watching students bloom every day!” When asked why she chose to work for Capital School District, she said, “I am a product of Capital, DHS Class of 89. I believe in what Capital has to offer students and in my 24 years I have worked with some wonderful colleagues.” Mrs. Weekes teaches at Towne Point Elementary. #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare #SenatorPride

post_text: Welcome Mr. Mike Denman to WHMS! Mr. Denman is the new 5th Dean! #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare
shared_text:
William Henry Middle School
August 31 at 10:24 AM ·

Welcome Mr. Mike Denman, 5th grade Dean, at WHMS! A 2008 graduate of Caesar Rodney, Mr. Denman attended West Virginia University where he earned his degree in History and Political Science. In 2015, Mr. Denman graduated from Wilmington University with a masters in Special Education and became the head lacrosse coach in Capital School District, while officially beginning his teaching career. Mr. Denman enjoys sports, dogs, and spending time with his family. This summer he spent a lot of time golfing, playing lacrosse, fishing, and traveling. Mr. Denman shared, “This year I am most excited to start a new chapter with a new team. I'm excited about meeting the new students at William Henry, and doing everything I can to help them become more successful in school and in life. I can't wait to get started! It's going to be a great year!” Welcome Mr. Denman, we are happy to have you at WHMS!

Welcome, Mr. Brian Bowman, Immersion teacher at Fairview Elementary! We are pleased to have you join our Senator Nation. When asked why he became a teacher, Mr. Bowman said, “I became a teacher, because it is rewarding to me to see a child be successful and self confident because of something I have taught whether it be academic or behavioral.” Why he chose Capital School District: “I chose Capital, because I worked for Dr. Henderson 13 years ago (when she was a Principal). I value her leadership and appreciation for her teachers.”
#SenatorsCare #SenatorsLearn

post_text: Welcome Jeannette Stewart, 5th grade ELA and Social Studies teacher, at WHMS!
shared_text:
William Henry Middle School
August 27 at 8:08 AM ·

Welcome Jeannette Stewart, 5th grade ELA and Social Studies teacher, at WHMS! A graduate of the University of Delaware with a Bachelor’s degree in Elementary Teacher Education with a concentration in Middle School English and Special Education. Ms. Steward shared, “I am most excited about being able to teach back in my home state, alongside a wonderful group of educators, who I know will support each other through this difficult, digital-learning time.” Ms. Stewart spent her summer safely relocating back to DE from Florida where she was living for 3 years. She even squeezed time in this summer to hike almost 25 different trails! When asked why she chose Capital, Ms. Steward shared, “I couldn’t imagine a better district or team of colleagues to work with and learn from. I truly believe in the Senator mindset of providing for and meeting the needs of the whole child.” Welcome to Senator Nation Ms. Stewart, we are SO happy to have you!

Today we celebrate Mrs. Diane Lynch for both her birthday and her last day in Senator Nation! Mrs. Lynch shared, “I found that I loved the school atmosphere, students and energy of a school. The years have flown by, with adventures at South Dover, Dover High School Tan office and finally WHMS. 30 yrs have brought me to my next adventure, retirement.” Mrs. Lynch will now be enjoying retirement life at the beach! “I will miss my school family and the hustle and bustle of the school day. I am proud to now be a retired senator and can't wait to spend more time with my grands and my Capt. Bob. Take care, you all will be missed. Have a great, different school yr.” We appreciate your dedication and commitement over 30 years! Happy Birthday and Happy Retirement Mrs. Lynch!

Welcome, Ms. Olga Bermejo, Spanish Immersion First grade teacher at Fairview Elementary! We are happy that you have joined our Senator Nation!
Ms. Bermejo just moved to Delaware from Hawaii this past February. When asked why she liked teaching, she said, “I love teaching because it gives me the opportunity to share my knowledge with my students. Seeing their eyes light up when they understand the concepts and apply them feeds my soul. I also love to see my students grow and change from the beginning of year to the end of the year.” She told us that she decided to teach in the Capital School District because she wanted to be part of the community and help the next generation succeed. #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare #SenatorPride

post_text: Welcome, Ms. Morgan James! Ms. James is a Spanish teacher at Dover High School. We are pleased that she has joined our Senator Nation. Here is what she had to say about why she became a teacher: “I have always wanted to be a teacher. I think there is a special fulfillment as a teacher knowing you are a small part of someone's story. The influence of an adult who believes in you and challenges you to be your best can make all the difference in someone's success. When I began studying Spanish in college, I became passionate about being able to extend cultural awareness and language within the classroom.” About why she chose Capital School District: “Capital has always had a great reputation for the programs and courses offered to students. There is something super special about being able to teach in your hometown and I am looking forward to when we are back in the classroom and teaching face-to-face!” #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare #SenatorPride

post_text: Welcome to Dr. Shannon Hughes, Licensed Clinical Social Worker at East Dover Elementary! We are pleased that she has joined our Senator Nation. When asked why she chose to work for Capital School District, she said, “I am thrilled to be working for the Capital School District. I was drawn to the Senator Nation, for its progressive views on Mental Health, focus on the Whole Child and comprehensive approach to education. As an experienced Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW) and Educator, it was important for me to select a District that highly values the Health and Well-being of its students. We are in unprecedented times. However, I rest assured knowing that in the Capital School District, we are excited and committed to supporting each other and our students.“ #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare #SenatorPride

post_text: Team Rubicon has arrived in our area! This nationwide veteran volunteer emergency response team is here to help with storm cleanup after a tornado ravaged our community during Tropical Storm Isaias. District Coordinator Ryan Barkman explained how they help. After disaster strikes, a member of the team answers the call for help by visiting the area to assess damage and to identify projects for the response team. That person will decide then the size of the team and the required expertise. Team Rubicon started their efforts in the Moore’s Lake area where multiple trees have fallen. Kudos to Team Rubicon. They are amazing veteran volunteers who continually give service to communities everywhere. Capital School District is thrilled that Team Rubicon is currently staying at Dover High School. Thank you, Team Rubicon, for assisting our community. #SenatorsCare

post_text: Capital School District cherishes the historical importance of our schools and was deeply saddened by the damage caused to William Henry Middle School and Booker T Washington from Tropical Storm Isaias. The State is currently assessing the damage to determine our next steps and has authorized water and debris cleanup. Servpro has been working diligently to clean and remove all the debris. A structural engineer has also completed an initial assessment and is working on a report for the school district. We remain committed to doing all that we can to protect the rich history of our schools and community. #SenatorsCare #SenatorsLearn

Delaware State University EFNEP is offering 4 to 6 weeks of Free Nutrition Classes to you and your family and friends regardless of income. All classes are 100% free!
Topics of Focus include: Nutrition education: Diabetes, hypertension, weight loss, eating health, portion control, managing high cholesterol, food groups; Food budgeting/ Menu planning; Interactive Food lessons; Cooking Demonstration; Exciting Recipes; Food Safety Practices Review; 7 Tips to a Healthy Lifestyle and many surprises.
If you are interested in participating in these classes, please send an email to efnep@desu.edu.

"I’ve thoroughly enjoyed being back at WHMS surrounded by students and staff. I’ve had the pleasure of working with 8 students along with Mrs. Seeney and Ms. Davis. Together we have been brushing up on our ELA and Math power standards. The students seem to enjoy Camp Adventure the most, specifically taking virtual field trips together to places including The White House, The Amazon Rainforest, Sea World, Tokyo Disneyland, and more!"

Thanks, Ms. Stoffa, for working with our children. #Senatorslearn #SenatorsCare

post_text: Ms. Lena Hall teaches 4th grade for the Virtual Summer Boost program. “The kids have enjoyed getting to know students from the other elementary schools during our Zoom meetings. We have been focusing on Main Idea and Details as well as working with fractions using a variety of different programs and applications to make it as interactive as possible. This whole experience has really challenged us as teachers to find ways to really engage the students and make the learning authentic and meaningful. I'm really proud to be part of the Capital School District family and am impressed with the way in which everyone is actively trying to do what is best for our students and our families.” #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare

post_text: Ms. Elizabeth Long is the Summer Boost Visual Arts Teacher for the on-site and hybrid K-4 students. "I am so excited to be able to provide art education to our Summer Boost students! We are figuring out this virtual education world together while students are experiencing the arts and creating amazing work.” She explained that kindergartners and first graders used shapes and patterns to create beautiful drawings. Second and fourth grade students learned about using their eyes to observe and draw objects in the room through a drawing practice called Blind Contour. “This week we are preparing sketches inspired by Wayne Thiebaud,” she said. “Next week we are turning our sketches into sculpture using Model Magic.” She wanted to give a shout-out to Capital's Paraprofessionals who are assisting her in her art classes. She told us that a virtual gallery is coming soon.

Meet Karin Synoski!
Ms. Synoski is a Summer Boost At-Home Remote Learning teacher for Dover High School. “I am teaching the Summer School Algebra 2 course online which is similar to what students worked on from home once we went to online learning in March,” she said. “The students that are engaged regularly are doing well and enjoy the flexibility of the online program. As a teacher, I am here to help and wish more kids would reach out if they have questions as they are working at home.”

Thank you, Ms. Karin Synoski, for working with our students! #SenatorsLearn #SenatorsCare

Capital School District Summer Boost Hybrid and In-School programs begin on Monday, July 13th, 2020 and run for 3 weeks. These sessions join the already in progress Online Summer Boost Program to bring summer learning to our Senators. Information has been sent home via School Messenger to those families with students that are enrolled. If you missed this message, you can find it online at https://www.capital.k12.de.us/summerboost2020 .

Please note the safety guidelines about screening your student at home before coming to the In-School or Hybrid Session from our nurses. It is extremely important that we work together to provide a safe environment for our learners. More information can be found on our website (link above).

See you Monday! #SenatorsLearn #EvenInTheSummer

post_text:
Congratulations, Amanda Wells, School Psychologist of the Year for 2020-2021! Amanda serves diverse roles, integrating the ten domains of professional practice in the context of a team-based approach to meet the needs of the whole child holistically.

From Kent County Community School: “Amanda is definitely part of the “heart” of KCCS and we would not be able to do what we do without her. As a master of collaboration, she consistently goes above and beyond to build teams to serve the needs of our students and to create groups that work together frequently and well. Amanda believes in the ideas and expertise of others and exemplifies "team” with how she walks, talks, acts, and carries herself.”

Her professional activities include School Psychologist mentor, Internship supervisor, Professional Advocate, National Crisis Prevention Trainer, District Lead Psychologist, Chair of district's mental health committee, Threat Protocol and Debriefing subcommittee lead, School and district PD provide and Tier 2/3 team creator. She is KCCS’s Specialist of the Year.

June 3 at 11:26 AM ·

Curbside Pickup will begin next Monday, June 8th! Curbside services will be available Monday through Friday from 10 am - 1 pm and 3 - 6 pm.

.

1. Place your requests online using the library catalog, Delaware Libraries app, or AskALibrarian Delaware or call the library at (302) 736-7030.

2. Get notified when your items are available for pickup.

3. Schedule your pickup time by calling the library.

4. Curbside pickup is located at the rear entrance of the library by the parking lot. Spaces are marked on the sidewalk to accommodate social distancing. For the safety of patrons and staff, please approach the table only when directed by staff.

post_text:
DR. SYLVIA HENDERSON NAMED INTERIM SUPERINTENDENT OF CAPITAL SCHOOL DISTRICT

At tonight’s Board of Education meeting, a unanimous vote appointed Dr. Sylvia Henderson to the Interim Superintendent position with the departure of Dr. Dan Shelton on July 1st, 2020. Please help us congratulate Dr. Henderson in continuing to bring the Capital School District forward to meet the needs of the whole child and expanding our dedication to the children and community that encompasses the Senator Nation. Dr. Henderson began her career at Capital in 2015 as Assistant Superintendent of the Capital School District and has helped bring our district forward since her first day in office. She bleeds blue and white and exudes Senator pride each day and we are excited to move forward with Dr. Henderson into the 2020-21 School Year.

DR. SYLVIA HENDERSON NAMED INTERIM SUPERINTENDENT OF CAPITAL SCHOOL DISTRICT

At tonight’s Board of Education meeting, a unanimous vote appointed Dr. Sylvia Henderson to the Interim Superintendent position with the departure of Dr. Dan Shelton on July 1st, 2020. Please help us congratulate Dr. Henderson in continuing to bring the Capital School District forward to meet the needs of the whole child and expanding our dedication to the children and community that encompasses the Senator Nation. Dr. Henderson began her career at Capital in 2015 as Assistant Superintendent of the Capital School District and has helped bring our district forward since her first day in office. She bleeds blue and white and exudes Senator pride each day and we are excited to move forward with Dr. Henderson into the 2020-21 School Year.

post_text:
The Choir School of Delaware is excited to announce its 2020 Summer Program in partnership with SummerCollab, the United Way of Delaware’s After School Network, the Wilmington Public Library and DelawareShakespe are. The Summer Program is a virtual program for any children ages 7-17 (grades 2-12) in the state of Delaware. **This program is offered at no cost, but a commitment to daily attendance is required.**
The program will include
• Academic skills development
• Music
• Arts education
• Movement activities
• And More!
The program will help bridge the academic gap created by out-of-school time due to the COVID pandemic and prepare students for the next school year. The addition of other activities, including musical training in the tradition of the Choir School, will give students a camp experience during this period of continued social distancing.

For more information or to sign up, visit their website at https://choirschoolofdelaware.org/virtual-summer-program/

post_text: A special message from CMS teachers and staff to their eighth graders! #SenatorsCare
shared_text:
Central Middle School
June 15 at 11:41 PM ·

Today would have been the day that I said goodbye to my wonderful 8th grade class...but unfortunately, we are in circumstances beyond my control. Although you finished middle school today, know that you’ll always be my student!

So a special message to our 8th graders- We are so proud of you. You have shown that you can make your way through one of the most stressful times we’ve seen in a school year. The CMS teachers, staff, and administration are so very proud of all you have accomplished!

I wish you the very best next year in high school. Remember that you are capable of being anything you want to be. You are special and will offer the world great things!

While the world outside is in chaos, remember that behind the walls of CMS are people who care for you, love you, and are proud of you! In the hard times, remember that you can make it! In the easy times, remember to have fun.

We wish you the very best and if you ever need us...you know where to find us!

post_text: Requesting Related Art Classes in Home Access Center - Central Middle School #SenatorsCare
shared_text:
Central Middle School
May 28 at 1:24 PM ·

CMS family,

All current 6th and 7th graders will have one last opportunity to request Related Arts Courses for the 2020-21 school year. All forms to do this were mailed out in April but I am including them again here. If you need to get your Home Access Center login info, please call the school in which your student is currently enrolled.

The window to do this will close at 5:00 on June 15. There will not be another opportunity so please make sure you get the info you need to complete this process now.

After this, we will schedule students into Related Arts courses randomly and based on availability.

Please don’t miss out on the chance to select the classes you take for middle school!

We offer more options than any other middle school around!! Middle School is your time to explore all career options and make decisions about what you like and don’t like.

We look forward to working with each of you next year!!

If you have questions, please contact me at Shan.green@capital.k12.de.us
Or leave me a message here on the CMS FB page.

Thank you!!
Shan

post_text: Next week is Teacher Appreciation Week (May 4th-8th). We love our teachers! Please see the post from the Delaware Department of Education below. Let's honor our teachers.
shared_text:
Delaware Department of Education (DDOE)
April 30 at 7:49 AM ·

National Teacher Appreciation Week is May 4 to 8. This year more than ever families are aware of the incredible work and talents of our teachers. While traditional in-person celebrations aren't possible this year due to school building closures and the State of Emergency, help us show appreciation for the great educators in your lives this year. Please submit your stories online here. We will compile and share them. And don't forget to use the hashtag #IloveDEteachers when you share your own posts on facebook, Twitter and Instagram. Here is the online submission form: https://www.doe.k12.de.us//cms/module/selectsurvey/TakeSurvey.aspx?SurveyID=240 #IloveDEteachers

post_text:
We are working with the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services, Division of Public Health to collect public opinion regarding mental health challenges faced by some youth and the stigma surrounding mental health issues. Breaking the silence around mental health issues among teens can help facilitate access to treatment and prevent extreme situations.

We developed a brief online survey about messages that promote better understanding and immediate treatment of teens suffering from mental health challenges. The survey is designed to be taken by teens age 12 to 17 and by adults who are involved with teens, such as teachers, coaches, counselors, or parents.
The survey should take less than 10 minutes and may be accessed at this link:
www.helpisherede.com/youthsurvey
The survey will close on April 30, 2020

Capital School District served over 800 meals today through the community meal delivery program ( http://bit.ly/csdmealdelivery ). We are extremely proud of our Nutrition Staff for working so diligently to serve our local children. Incase you didn't know, districts all over the state are working together to ensure all children 18 years and under are able to receive meals while schools are closed. You can find a list of programs on the DOE website at https://www.doe.k12.de.us/page/4149.

Capital's program will run Monday thru Friday while schools are closed. Please keep an eye on our website http://bit.ly/csdmealdelivery or http://bit.ly/csdstayhealthy for updates/changes to the delivery locations and times as they may adjust based on need.

post_text:
Message from Comcast Cable to Capital School District Residents and Families in response to Coronavirus / COVID-19 and the increased need for connectivity at home:

1. We will make it even easier for low-income families who live in a Comcast service area to sign up by offering new customers 60 days of complimentary Internet Essentials service, which is normally available to all qualified low-income households for $9.95/month.

2. Also, we are increasing Internet speeds for the Internet Essentials service from 15/2 Mbps to 25/3 Mbps for all new and existing customers, which will be the speed of the service going forward.

Read more in the message below from Comcast. Customers can sign up for the service by visiting www.internetessentials.com or call 1-855-846-8376 for English and 1-855-765-6995 for Spanish.

post_text: This week the FCS students learned about Black History Month through cooking cultural dishes with a purpose. More information below!
shared_text:
William Henry Middle School
February 20 at 9:07 AM ·

This week the FCS students learned about Black History Month through cooking cultural dishes with a purpose.
Mrs. Ikechi-Konkwo, 6th grade teacher from Nigeria, prepared a Nigerian dish for Class 405 which was delicious. It consisted of rice, chicken, and beef. She also explained the history behind the dish and how it is very common in Nigeria.
Courtney and Adriana, chefs from Michele’s and the Steakhouse at Dover Downs, prepared a traditional Southern dish of shrimp and grits. The students in Class 306 loved it.
Thank you all so much for sharing your expertise with us!

post_text: The rocket launch is rescheduled for tomorrow at 3:21pm.
shared_text:
NASA's Wallops Flight Facility was live.
February 13 at 3:08 PM ·

***Update: Launch is now scheduled for 3:21 p.m. EST on Saturday, Feb. 15. Live coverage begins at 2:45.

Watch a cargo spacecraft lift off from NASA's Wallops Flight Facility in Virginia on a resupply mission to the International Space Station! 🚀

Launch is targeted at 3:43 p.m. EST on Friday, Feb. 14 for Northrop Grumman's 13th commercial resupply services mission. A previous launch attempt on Feb. 9 was scrubbed after off-nominal readings from a ground support sensor. The Cygnus cargo spacecraft, loaded with approximately 7,500 pounds of research, supplies and hardware, will launch atop an Antares rocket from the Mid-Atlantic Regional Spaceport. This Cygnus spacecraft is named the S.S. Robert H. Lawrence, in honor of the first African American to be selected as an astronaut.

post_text: What an adventure for these Hartly students! Skyping with a museum in Wyoming! A great, new and fun way to learn!
shared_text:
Hartly Elementary School
February 4 at 8:01 AM ·

Third grade went on a virtual Skype field trip to Cody, Wyoming’s Buffalo Bill Center for the West. Students have been learning about Native American tribes and were able to chat with their museum educator! Students listened to legends and examined artifacts used by the tribes of the Great Plains including bison mittens, sinew rope, bison skin parfleche bag, tail fly swatters and a bison bladder water bottle. Thank you, @centerofthewest !
Powered by @skypeintheclassroom

post_text: Earlier this week Central Middle School held their Geography Bee. The top ten finalists who competed were Justin Didden, Gary Guo, Raven Neumeister, Isis Jacome, Chris Connelly, Vincent Troy, Francis Mailom, Ben Li, Isaiah Williams and Ronin Poliquin. Congratulations to these students! The competition heralded a first, second and third place winner. Congratulations to Gary Guo who won third place and Isaiah Williams who won second! And congratulations to Justin Didden who won first place! Justin won first place at CMS last year and he won at the state level as well. He will advance once again to the state competition. Congratulations to everyone! Well done!

post_text: SIPS (Students Increasing their Potential for Success) Coffee Shop is a unified class that combines our STAR program students with our Dover High students to form a cohesive team. The goal of the SIPS coffee shop is to provide entry level job readiness skills to our students. These skills include but are not limited to; customer service, money management, inventory taking, proper hygiene and operating, maintaining and cleaning industrial coffee makers. STAR stand for Students Transitioning to Adult Readiness. Each weekday morning, these students visit classrooms and offices in different areas of the school to see if anyone would like to buy a coffee or tea from the coffee shop. While students take orders, others make coffee. Everyone works as a team to ensure that the SIPS Coffee Shop is a huge success and judging from the reactions in many of the classrooms, it most definitely is!

post_text:
Tomorrow (Saturday) is Super Senator Day! Come out and see us at Dover High School from 10am to 2pm. There will be many vendors, displays, musical performances, the DHS Drum Line, and MANY community partners for you to visit.

One feature we are excited to announce is the giveaway of a 2 in 1 Chromebook from our friends at Dell to one of our Capital School District students and their family! Please visit the Office of Technology table at the event to find out the rules and how to enter. You have to be there to get the info, we hope to see you there!

Don't forget, we also have a FREE lunch for everyone while you enjoy the event. #SenatorsSoar #SuperSenatorDay2019 #SenatorsSoar2019

EMPLOYMENT OPPORTUNITY: Capital School District is seeking candidates for multiple positions in the Office of Technology. Have you ever wanted to provide hands-on advanced tech support for schools, their staff, and students? Now is your chance!

Learn more about the Level 2 Systems Technician position here: https://www.applitrack.com/joindelawareschools/OnlineApp/JobPostings/View.asp?AppliTrackJobId=5006

Learn more about the Level 1 Field Technician position here (recent college graduate after studying IT? look here!): https://www.applitrack.com/joindelawareschools/OnlineApp/JobPostings/View.asp?AppliTrackJobId=5145
